The 87th United States Congress adopted the following resolution on September 15, 1961: &quot;Resolved by the Senate and the House of Representatives that the Congress salutes Uncle Sam Wilson of Troy, New York, as the progenitor of America's National symbol of Uncle Sam.&quot;

<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Wilson" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Wilson</a>


Because of its overwhelming popularity, the image was later adapted for use in World War II. Upon presenting President Franklin Delano Roosevelt a copy of the poster, Flagg remarked that he had been his own model for Uncle Sam to save the modeling fee. Roosevelt was impressed and replied: &quot;I congratulate you on your resourcefulness in saving model hire. Your method suggests Yankee forebears.&quot;

<a href="http://www.loc.gov/exhibits/treasures/trm015.html" rel="nofollow">www.loc.gov/exhibits/treasures/trm015.html</a>


I'm guessing she was joking, I can't find anything about a NJ Uncle Sam story. Maybe the Mayor looks like Uncle Sam.
